# Batch All Changes — Minimize Recompilation

Chromium builds are slow and expensive. Plan thoroughly and deliver all changes in a single pass.

## Before Writing Code

1. **Read all relevant files first** — understand the full scope before making any edit
2. **Identify every file that needs modification** — list them explicitly
3. **Plan the dependency order** — know which changes depend on others (headers, BUILD.gn, implementations)
4. **Check for missing includes, forward declarations, and BUILD.gn entries** upfront

## During Implementation

- Edit **all related files in one batch** — do not submit partial changes that require follow-up rounds
- When adding a new class or feature, deliver everything together: header, implementation, BUILD.gn entry, and any call-site changes
- When modifying a `.patch` file, also update any corresponding `src/dao/` files that depend on the patched code
- Ensure all method signatures, includes, and symbol references are consistent across files before finishing

## Common Pitfalls to Avoid

- Missing `#include` for newly used types
- Adding a source file but forgetting the BUILD.gn entry
- Declaring a method in a header but not implementing it (or vice versa)
- Changing a function signature in one file but not updating all callers
- Forgetting namespace qualifiers or forward declarations

## Verification Checklist

Before considering the task complete, confirm:

- [ ] All new/modified files are syntactically consistent with each other
- [ ] BUILD.gn lists every new source file
- [ ] All `#include` directives are present
- [ ] No dangling references to renamed or removed symbols
- [ ] Patch files and `src/dao/` files are both updated if needed
